Refactor the NixOS module at nix/module.nix to use builtins.toJSON instead of manual YAML string templating.

## Problem

The current config generation (lines 162-182) uses Nix multiline string concatenation with manual indentation to produce YAML. This is fragile — we just had a bug where telegram fields were rendered at the wrong indentation level because Nix's `''` string literal strips leading whitespace when concatenating separate blocks.

## Solution

Replace the string template with a Nix attribute set serialized via `builtins.toJSON`. The reel-life Go binary uses `gopkg.in/yaml.v3` which accepts JSON (YAML is a superset of JSON), so this works without any Go changes.

Replace lines 162-182 of `nix/module.nix` with something like:

```nix
environment.etc."reel-life/config.yaml".text = builtins.toJSON ({
  sonarr = { base_url = cfg.sonarrUrl; };
  chat = {
    backend = cfg.chatBackend;
  } // lib.optionalAttrs (cfg.chatBackend == "telegram") {
    telegram_chat_id = cfg.chatTelegramChatID;
    telegram_allowed_users = cfg.chatTelegramAllowedUsers;
  };
  agent = {
    model = cfg.agentModel;
    max_tokens = cfg.agentMaxTokens;
  };
  monitor = {
    enabled = cfg.monitorEnabled;
    interval = cfg.monitorInterval;
  };
  log = {
    level = cfg.logLevel;
    format = cfg.logFormat;
  };
  server = {
    port = cfg.listenPort;
  };
});
```

Use `lib.optionalAttrs` for all conditional sections. No string interpolation, no whitespace management.

## Important details

- The file extension can stay as `config.yaml` — Go's yaml.v3 will parse JSON fine
- Check all the NixOS module options defined above line 162 to make sure every option is represented in the JSON output
- Also check the cosmo host config at https://github.com/patflynn/cosmo/blob/main/hosts/classic-laddie/default.nix (lines 115-130) for any options that need to be wired through — there are options like radarrUrl, prowlarrUrl, overseerrUrl etc. that may exist in the module but might not be in the template currently
- The notebook config should also be included if the module has options for it (check if the recent notebook PR added module options)
- Run `go build ./...` and `go test ./...` to verify the Go side still parses the config correctly

## Acceptance criteria
- No string interpolation or manual YAML in the module
- All existing module options are represented in the JSON output
- Conditional sections (telegram, notebook, etc.) use lib.optionalAttrs
- `go build ./...` and `go test ./...` pass
- The generated config file is valid and parseable by the Go binary
